column2: i sit on the hot-metal swing
column3: my bare feet helping it sway back and forth as my hand holds an orange popsicle
column4: tongue busy in licking the fruity taste.

column2: trying to pass her summer in mini dresses and pigtails
column3: comic books and video games when i see another little girl. she joins me on the swings
column4: her uneven-toothy smile charming me. i offer her a taste of my popsicle
column5: watching her smile getting brighter. together
column7: racing to slide down first. we ask each other's names and favourite cartoons.

column1: i excitedly squeal when she tells me she loves reading 'goosebumps'.
our knees get scraped till the sun sets and our mothers arrive to take us home. we say our goodbyes. i tell my mother of my new friend all the way back home
column2: my feet never stops bouncing. mother shakes her head at me
column3: her eyes carrying a strange love for me even when she's annoyed that i'm running on the street. i finally tell her my new friend also likes reading goosebumps. maybe we can buy her the new part. mother says ""okay"".

column4: to the park that's been abandoned by happy laughter for years now. i slowly walk towards the creaking swing
column5: carefully sitting on it. i let my feet slip out of my sandals and barefoot sway the swing again. my hair have long forgotten the innocence of pigtails. after a few minutes of quietness
column6: a girl my age sits on the swing beside me
column7: her eyes meeting mine with a sweet familiarity. i don't have a popsicle to share
column8: so i lend her an ear. she talks
column10: lonely ghosts of the attic. she tells me how she was robbed off her dignity and happy days by a bad man. she tells me how growing up has told her a tale more haunting than goosebumps. she tells me how she is now a victim of her own thoughts every night - reminding her of her stolen childhood. i silently drop a tear. ""me too."" i say.

column2: we find something to share. when i return home that evening
column3: i tell my mother about my old friend - how she too carries the same scars. maybe we can help her heal. mother says ""okay"".";;en;;;;;;0;;wordsmith_ana;ANUSHKA J.;;0;False;7;0;0;106;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/50796dea974a267d97ab5d36073be570/5D1DCD06/t51.2885-15/e35/42658360_1897586953689326_1055103548426656640_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"in the dry summer of 2004

column1: while we don’t intend to dilute the #metoo movement and whatever it stands for
column2: it is still ideal to not jump to conclusions about any situation before it has been given enough time to breathe. as there is no fixed way of determining the difference between true or false
column3: without being presented both sides of the picture. what we’re trying to say is
column4: it is ideal if we hear all the parties involved in the incident out
column5: before passing any sort of judgment.

column2: taking the legal route to deal with such disputes would make things more clear-cut for everyone. yes
column3: it is understandable why the legal route is an unpreferred destination
column4: but going there would leave the judgment to a system built to protect us
column5: the citizens. it would also allow for the judgment to be made by professionals instead of people with an internet connection. let’s be real
column6: the internet holds a lot of power but one tweet can ruin someone’s life so going to authority could be the right way to go about things.

column1: if you feel that stories like this need to come out
column2: a tweet can do a lot but taking a legal route and talking to a lawyer may help you gain closure. several lawyers across india have been willing to go pro bono and consult victims to help them take the legal route. lawyers have also stressed the impact of the internet and it’s netizens when it comes to both the accuser and accused as it can have a hazardous impact on their respective personal and professional futures.

column3: what do you think should men in our society should actually be doing to resolve this?

column1: today is world  mental health day and i want to take this opportunity to talk a bit about this. just to clarify
column2: it's got nothing to do with gender and vulnerability but more about how much we are suffering on the inside but what we all portray on the outside. in today's world of social media where all of us are subjected to this ideal lifestyle of fancy vacations
column5: perfect relationships and happy shiny faces all the time
column6: most of us become victims of consuming this as our ultimate goal to a happy life. we all want to live someone else's life and i am also equally guilty of being part of this portrayal. especially when i was suffering severely from within the last couple of months but what i put out was a version of me in full work mode
column7: shooting with best of the companies and enjoying the perks of being a photographer. what i didn't show was
column8: the pressure of delivering at work
column10: battling at family and personal front.

column1: bts: i shot this with people who i thought would do justice to this series and also who seemed relatable with relatable stories. it was a mix of both the gender before anyone picks out about the male gender crying as if it's an unusual thing
column2: which i don't get at all.

column1: i have known corné for the longest time
column2: he was one of my first clients. when i showed him the series he immediately showed interest in it and wanted to be a part of it. he came over last week to my house and we talked for some time about life
column3: food and work till it was time to shoot. he asked me if i could put on this video of his late brother who passed away due to a severe illness. it was a homemade video of a collection of his brother's images and the moment he put it on and sat down he was crying. it was so immediate for him that i didn't even have to wait or instigate compared to the rest who took their time to get there. this has been the most simplest yet the toughest thing i have ever shot cause i felt i was invading someone's personal space and their teary eyes peircing right through that lens was questioning my soul and it's purpose. this is a conversational series and i would love to hear your stories in the comments.";;en;;;;;;0;;riddhi_parekh;Riddhi Parekh;;0;False;23;0;0;1139;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/b986e7e2f575db528c0a3eda94e1ea8f/5D286423/t51.2885-15/e35/42144770_331457077658019_6426968413888007890_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"i am fine.

so this is one of my #whyididntreport stories. before i start
column2: i would like to ask anybody reading this to listen and believe survivors. because if you don't
column3: the nightmare goes on even worse for so many of them. please listen
column4: believe and support those who experienced sexual abuse/harrasment/r*pe. we are all in this together and only together we can give survivors the strengh to speak up against their abusers. /

column1: ...because for long time the r*pe felt like a bad dream that just happened in my mind. ...because for a long time i didn't even realized i got r*ped
column2: i was too young. ...because i was not sure what happened at all when this man came out of the bushes near my path and pulled me behind them. ...because i depersonalized through the r*pe and i felt like this is happening to someone else. ...because my body didn't felt like mine within these two minutes. ...because i thought i got my period for the first time and not that this blood was caused by the r*pe.

column1: but especially; i didn't report because i felt like it was my own fault. that the dress i wore must have felt like an invitation
column2: because i was dumb enough to think it would be safe to walk home alone at 10pm as a 12 year old girl. i didn't report because i was ashamed and that nobody would believe me since my dress didn't get dirty. i didn't report because when i finally found my strengh to talk about it
column3: the first questions were ""what did you wear?""
column4: ""how short was that dress?"" ""oh but why don't you seem to be traumatized?"" ""but why then you have a boyfriend now with whom you can have sex?"". i didn't report because after over 4 years
column5: it would be impossible to find any proof for the r*pe. i didn't report because i deeply tried to just forget this man's face
column6: to just find a way out of this night by night upcoming nightmare. i didn't report because i thought that in the end it wouldn't change anything
column7: not what happened to my body. i didn't report because i was scared my dad would try to find and end my abuser.

column1: i didn't report because society silenced my 12 year old me.

column1: 302054;instagram;2018-10-10 16:22:28;FALSE;"#metoo: kashmir women's collective puts out list of harassment cases; allegations crop up against several scribes
as the #metoo movement gains momentum in india
column2: the kashmir women's collective has also collated a list of cases ranging ""from frivolous chats with absolute disregard to the girl's discomfort
column4: to attempts at physical assaults and forceful inappropriate touching"". the collective said that the information is being made public so that other women and girls are made aware that any man – no matter if he is an intellectual
column9: teacher – can be an abuser. the aim is also to publicly shame the abusers and ""pressurise them and others into behaving more responsibly"". representational image. getty images

column1: the collective further goes on to say that kashmir's #metoo is different because: -""this can be seen as a mass attack on kashmiri community by some right-wing indians which we do not support. no islamophobia or kashmir put down
column2: please."" -""it can be seen as an attempt to take away attention from the political movement."" the collective said that that is not the purpose at all. ""in fact
column3: we are wary that this will be seen from the context of the political affiliation of abusers and molesters. we are not concerned about an abuser's political inclination
column4: family name or beliefs. abusers come from all spheres of life
column5: even the ones apparently fighting for justice and equality."" the first case mentioned in the list involves gowher geelani
column6: a political analyst. 'anonymous' asked him for help once and after that
column7: he kept sending her weird messages and started to call randomly
column8: making her extremely uncomfortable. another 'anonymous' person quoted in the list said gowher kept texting her and asking her to meet.

column1: the next case is that of journalist sameer yasir

column1: 302073;instagram;2018-10-10 15:59:25;FALSE;we all go through times where we need to re-evaluate our lives and the ways we are treating our bodies and minds. some of us are open about these struggles
column2: some of us not. some of us face these challenges head on
column3: and some of us choose to cope with these struggles by finding distractions
column4: most of which can only temporarily make us feel better. that’s where you can find me. i am somewhere between realizing i need to take different steps to properly care for myself and accept the things i cannot change
column5: and actually making those changes happen. i know i speak for many when i say life is hard
column6: and also when i say it is hard to find the help you need after realizing you need it. you are not alone. i am here with you
column7: wondering and hoping i feel like my authentic self again soon. it’s taken me so long to realize that my feelings are valid and that i do serve a purpose here. it’s not every day i feel this
column8: though. sometimes i wake up and things have already happened in the world that directly influence me and my life. how do we change this vicious cycle? with compassion
column9: love for ourselves and one another
column11: education and community. we must be there for one another. we must share helpful resources with each other. create safe spaces. share stores and ideas. communicate. we must be bigger in numbers. love harder. listen more. speak up and let our voices be heard. reach out for help. let ourselves be cured. community can heal
column12: and it will. we have each other. i am here for you. i believe you. you are valid. i love you. #worldmentalhealthday #mentalhealthawareness #ibelieveher #metoo #community #iloveyou;;en;#worldmentalhealthday

column1: 302189;instagram;2018-10-10 15:06:32;FALSE;today is world mental health day 💗 so let me share a little with you in hopes to touch someone’s heart that may need it. yesterday my run outside was terrible- everything about it. at mile 4 a song came on that i hadn’t heard since i was 17 years old. 17.. one of the worst years of my life thus far.. i was in a sexually abusive relationship at the time. this song i would listen to regularly while driving back home from this monsters house. when it first started playing i was ok.. then the chorus came and i broke. i have heard of people crying on the side of the road while running
column3: but never have i done it. not until yesterday.  the amount of pain i felt could only be released through tears. i thought this man cared about me .. i thought that’s what love was ... but i didn’t understand why it hurt so badly. wanting to feel love... and i thought i could only feel that from him. i believed my value was dependent on making him happy and what he thought of me. just typing that makes my eyes tear up because it’s so untrue... and sad. placing myself back in that car driving home late at night ... feeling all that pain but thinking it was ok. after 3 years of hell and a restraining order to follow along with several other fucked up relationships & suppressing the sexual abuse for 10+ years i have been fighting like hell for my mental and physical well being. i always will be. i had a lot of learning to do ..i have done it... and i’m still fucking doing it. every.day. it’s not easy but what’s my other option????? quitting...depression.. drugs.. alcohol... toxic relationships???... been there. i’m not going back to that. i will always be working
column4: always fighting. if you are struggling..... ask for help... reach out... .. and please don’t give up on yourself 💜 #worldmentalhealthday2018 #metoo stillirun;;en;#worldmentalhealthday2018

column2: i’ve been on the brink of falling apart at any given moment. i’ve never been sexually assaulted and yet i have this visceral reaction to what transpired over the past several weeks. i have lived 31 years in a female body. this is what i remember.

column1: i remember from a young age men commenting on my body and looks. older men who said
column2: “if only i was younger…” or “i bet you have all the boys chasing after you.” i suppose they meant it as a compliment. they made me feel uncomfortable. i escaped those conversations as soon as i felt like i could without being rude.

column1: i remember parties in college that felt like a predatory environment. freshmen girls getting drunk and upperclass boys waiting for their opportunity to get them alone. i never took a sip because i sensed the danger.
i remember a walkway through a group of trees on my college campus. we jokingly referred to it as the “rape trail.” now
column2: there is a section of sidewalk at the end of my block that is bordered on one side by a heavily wooded canyon. i think of it as the “rape trail.” i avoid it at night or run through it with something in hand to use as a weapon.

column1: i remember being catcalled on the street every day for an entire semester when i studied abroad. after returning to my campus in the us
column2: my body would reflexively cringe as i approached a group of men on campus. i would relax again only after reminding myself that i was home now.

column1: i remember the countless times i’ve felt shamed by someone telling me to cover up. that i had inadvertently exposed a part of my body someone else deemed as inappropriate for public consumption. the immediate guilt even though i had never intentionally tried to be seductive. the message that my body needs to be policed in ways that a man’s body does not. that my body would attract attention just by existing and my intentions didn’t matter.

i don’t live in fear. i don’t like the reminders that maybe i should. when women share their story and aren’t believed/when men mock women who share/when i try to envision a better future for my daughter…i’m tempted to live in fear. swipe right for words that make me cry by @haleyjakobson.";;en;;@haleyjakobson.;;;;0;;chelseakimlong;Chelsea Long;;0;False;33;0;0;585;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/b2e0453c2cea0ecce4235b1b6d4c6832/5D0A0228/t51.2885-15/e35/42161349_1609076696058470_5623366577224380072_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"since hearing dr. blasey-ford’s testimony

column1: i see a mom pounding back a pot of coffee as a guilty pleasure. .
i see kids looking over my shoulder and watching my every move even if it's just their pictures. .

being a mom is the toughest job out there. i am no picture perfect mom. most days i'm saying there goes the bus now get ready. i'm allowing too much screen time. i give the kids food with food coloring. i let them stay up past their bed time. oh and speaking of bed i still allow them to cosleep with me. .
but when did mothering become something with so many rights and wrongs. isn't it our jobs as mothers to raise our kids to the best of our ability and try our best to not raise a bunch of jerks?! .
so here's a cheers to you moms. if all you did was keep your kiddos up right today i am saying to you

when i actually stopped being stubborn because i'd be blue in the face hyperventalating
column3: and inhaled deeply and slowly it would work!!! my heart rate would slow
column4: the pink would come back to my cheeks and my racing thoughts would subside.

column2: but take a moment to breathe and realize the only thing harming you is your thoughts. breathe and change your inner dialogue. breathe.....breathe.

column1: 302233;instagram;2018-10-10 14:55:57;FALSE;"ava and i have been having a difficult time lately. steven's been traveling a lot for work and captain mcderp here thinks it's a great idea to cuddle sweetly one minute then scream and knock stuff off the counter the next. .

and on top of that is strain between me and certain family members who felt the need to discuss the kavanaugh hearing. i feel so deeply for dr. ford and other women in this country who have just been told that their experiences
column3: aren't worth hearing. i've been assaulted several times (and mostly by drunk college frat boys) and i know this happens to most women at some point in their lives. but the official us response: ""we don't care and we will mock you for coming forward.""

column2: i don't want to really discuss politics on my blog
column3: but i feel this is so completely inextricable from the principles i write about that i had to bring it up. my own anxiety
column5: and those of my sisters i hope to lift up all echoed loudly during the news coverage.

column1: and if you feel the same
column2: go vote. elect representatives who speak to you and speak for you. .

column1: 302240;instagram;2018-10-10 14:57:39;FALSE;"sakhi volunteer #dvam #spotlight: ""my therapist was the one who helped me understand why i thought the violence was ok… why i ‘put up’ with the physical and emotional violence. i kept thinking to myself
column2: “how could i let myself be treated like that?” through therapy i understood “how could i not have? i have been watching this kind of violence since the day i was born."" .

column1: people have a huge misconception that once the violence is over
column2: life just goes back to regular programming. that’s not true. you work on recovering forever
column3: and that's not necessarily a bad thing. it’s a good thing to continue to work on yourself. but
column5: you don’t just go back to normal life. you have to relearn love
column8: and so many other things. you have to learn how to give these things and expect these things.

column1: if i could give my younger self one piece of advice
column3: ""get therapy earlier!"" i would tell myself ""you matter. you’re important. you deserve to be loved and respected by everyone. love always comes from within first."" .

column2: i finally feel like a caterpillar turned into a butterfly. i feel like i am ready to volunteer with sakhi and do the things i have always wanted to do."" 🦋 -- sakhi volunteer
column3: sahreen quadir (sahreen has given sakhi permission to share her name and story)

column2: i’d like to share with you something i’ve learned. you don’t have to agree with me to be my ally. you don’t have to reach a comfort level with my story either. it can make you squirm and you can still be my ally. you also don’t have to understand me or where i’m coming from. all you have to do is listen
column3: take me in. trust what you know of me. who i am. believe me. take me seriously. and act accordingly.

column2: known for his villainous and comic roles
column3: while shooting for the journey of karma. it was a love making scene involving poonam and the veteran actor. before the scene was canned

column6: poonam saw to it that the actor does not take any liberties with her. yet he did not miss the opportunity and made reel feel like real.

column3: has not forgotten the incident. and not wanting to come face to face with the character actor
column4: has chosen to avoid attending the trailer launch of the film just a week back. earlier she had  skipped the poster launch of the film too.

column1: this has been on my mind daily lately and i’ve debated ever sharing this story and told myself i never would because i use this platform for so much joy and was afraid to dampen that and always thought this moment was my fault
column2: but after so much of what has happened lately i started to feel my heart open up to talk about it
column3: and when @goodr released their use your words glasses
column4: i decided i could use this as an opportunity to use my words in case others needed to hear them
column5: and maybe to help find a little moment of relief if i got it off my chest •

column1: when i was younger and in college
column3: i ended up in a social situation that was uncomfortable with two men i had just met. one of them was nice and polite
column4: the other was not. it was not the night of fun and partying i anticipated it to be. i remember being in that dark room and wanting nothing more than to leave but i was terrified. the nice guy told the other guy to leave me alone but he wasn’t having any of it. i’ll never forget what i was wearing and the smells in that room. though the situation eventually ended mildly
column5: mostly with me trying to stay composed and keeping my composure
column6: the real kicker came when they told me to sign papers saying that i had consented to being with them so that i could never retaliate from that moment.  that
column8: has stood in my mind forever because i’ve spent the last decade+ thinking i had okayed that night because my name was on that piece of paper. i wish i could turn back time to tell myself it wasn’t my fault because it’s sat on my mind for so long that it was. so
column9: i share this to as goodr says
column11: and tell others it’s not your fault no matter if you’re crying and signing your name on a stupid piece of paper saying you agreed to everything
column12: because it’s your body and you are strong and powerful and amazing and worthy of nothing but the best and no one can ever take that way from you. #vanessagoesfromfattofit #goodrflamboyance #useyourwords #tellyourstory #metoo #iamhereforyou";;en;#vanessagoesfromfattofit

column1: 302305;instagram;2018-10-10 14:16:24;FALSE;i need to do my part to advance the issues that affect and concern me.  i’ve struggled in these past two years. i have marched
column4: joined the organizations whose work aligns with my beliefs
column5: and talked to people who have different viewpoints in order to understand how we got here. but there’s so much more to do and the traditional paths to change seem worn out and ineffective. some days i could swear we are living in an alternate universe.  when i’m down i go deep inside myself and words get turned off—so i make things instead.  i created a quilt pattern and i’m going to make zippered project-sized bags.  i will sell them for $50 and 100% of that will be donated to the national women’s law center. if you’re interested i’ll take preorders. please dm me. #craftivism #timesuplegaldefensefund #metoo #novemberiscoming #getoutthevote @nationalwomenslawcenter  edited to add: i will take initial pre-orders for up to 10 bags.;;en;#craftivism

column1: it had happened before... it was ignored before. the voices of raya sarkar and losha we're ignored among many others
more women in india face harassment than all the western countries combined.
then why are the cases of #metoo surfacing now?
is it the high amount of nepotism in bollywood which prevents the privileged celebrities from speaking up?
or is it the stigmas attached to sex

maybe it is the fact that rich men think of female bodies is theirs to look at and touch. they don't understand why they aren't appealing enough. they could be married or woke or talented af... and still do these things.
honestly it is probably just all of it.
it's not just their fault... it's the fault of every #indian who chooses to follow them and love them and give them a chance to benefit from their art.

and now as a #indiangirl i think it's my responsibility to make sure that this #metoomovement doesn't die down. it stays strong and alive for every girl secretly suffering and every girl silenced by men like these.

column2: i pulled out a notebook from my tenth grade creative writing class. contained in its pages were a few free writes about intense panic
column3: muffled sounds coupled with tingling limbs
column5: and feeling like generally i needed to do more. it would take me 13 more years to understand what i was writing about—those feelings and sensations i could not explain—was (is) anxiety. i didn’t have the language to explain what felt “off” and when i finally started to have access to the necessary language

column1: i’m sharing this because representation matters. i am a sometimes college teacher
column2: and interact with students fairly regularly. i want to do better for them
column3: to create spaces where a mental health struggle doesn’t become absented from the discussion of “how are you doing?” and to help make access to resources and options clear. my invisible identities— #metoo #firstgenstudent #anxietydisorder —are real and influence my pedagogy

column1: as someone who suffered in silence for a long time
column2: i want to use world mental health day as an opportunity to spread awareness and break the barrier of stigma around mental illness.

column1: after more than a year of on-going emotional
column3: i eventually got out of a bad relationship but ended up with depression
column4: anxiety and ptsd. all while still trying to get through my medical degree.

column2: feelings and actions that i couldn’t make sense of or rationalise was one of the most lonely experiences i’ve ever had. pretending to be okay when you’re not
column3: putting on a facade to get through the day and smiling through pain is physically and emotionally exhausting. it took some time but i eventually realised that it didn’t have to be that way and that i was choosing to fight my battles alone. being silent is a choice so if you are someone who is dealing with any degree of mental illness
column4: i’m asking you to choose differently.

column1: it’s not about attention-seeking or wanting sympathy
column2: it’s about owning your mental health like you would a broken leg. it’s about allowing yourself to access your support systems and about creating awareness about your state of mind. you don’t need to put it on social media - telling one person what you’re going through can be the most liberating experience and can help quieten the noise in your head. please don’t be afraid to ask for help
column3: whether it be from a friend
column4: your family or from a health professional.

column2: you are not being selfish and you are not over-reacting. don’t play down your suffering by comparing your life to someone else’s because you will always be able to find people in worse off situations
column3: but if everyone took that approach then no-one would get help. you will also be both shocked and comforted when you realise how many people are going through something similar.

column2: “this too shall pass.” it’s just four words but if you believe them
column3: you will find the strength to hold on because there are better days ahead. pain is temporary but hope is limitless.

column1: 302366;instagram;2018-10-10 13:40:50;FALSE;i’m not one to post things to personal.. people closest to me know i’ve been working on myself
column2: weekly going to see someone and work through my past trauma. this past week
column3: something came up during therapy that i have repressed for many years. living in a world where the media is shoved in our faces at all times it’s been even more overwhelming then i could of imagined. i’m not strong enough to share my stories publicly. i envy the strength of my fellow sisters who have been able to open up about their darkest times. i’m proud to be apart of their lives. i’ve never been one to follow politics
column4: but i believe i live on the independent line. i see both sides of the argument
column5: but when it comes to sexual assault it’s hard as a victim to wrap my head around some of the arguments from people who have never been through such trauma. my heart hurts right now that the people who run this country seem to turn a blind eye to victims. today i’m strong enough to say #metoo but i hope one day i can do more
column7: love myself more. this week i pushed through a comfort zone and broke down walls i had subconsciously built to protect myself. one day

column1: 302367;instagram;2018-10-10 13:41:46;FALSE;"thank you dr ford💪🏼 i signed this - hop over to @glennondoyle page if you are called to do the same 💌

millions of us spent last week imagining how it might feel to be dr. ford in this moment -- watching the aftermath of her world-shifting testimony unfold in this country. some warrior friends and i decided we must to do everything in our power to make sure dr. ford understands what her courage means to all of us. we need to make sure she hears -- directly from us -- that her heroic sacrifice was not in vain.
we know that while we fight against fear and hate and lies and greed- it is ever important to remember to actively love: to stop and honor those who stand mightily for hope

column2: we wrote dr. ford a love letter. our dream is that by the time dr. ford receives this letter
column3: she and her family will see that it’s been signed by every love warrior on earth. please take a moment
column5: to sit and read this letter. and then
column7: please sign your name. after the letter had made its way around the world
column8: we’ll get it to dr. blasey ford.

column1: you can read and sign the letter at the link in my bio above ☝🏼 and https://metoomvmt.org/
let us fight on and love on.

column7: please sign your name. after the letter had made its way around the world
column8: we’ll get it to dr. blasey ford.

column1: some of you could probably guess this post was coming and i know you will have seen similar posts today about this topic and i’m here to put in my two cents. ——————————

column2: has and will be a huge part of my life
column4: it hasn’t meant that i’m somehow stronger now. that’s not how mental health works
column5: as magical as that would be. once you’ve experienced trauma
column6: you are affected and your life is affected -negatively. i’m not going to come on here and lie that i’m “stronger now” or can “handle things” better because that’s not the truth of it. i have really bad days. i can’t watch a lot of tv shows or films because they affect me so much. i’m cautious and anxious a lot of the time but try not to show it. i’m not going to come on here and say i’m happy all the time
column7: why? because no one is happy all the time! that’s not real or honest
column8: that’s an instagram fantasy and you are not weird for feeling things other than happiness 100% of the time! you’re human!

column3: dissociation and on again off again depression. those things don’t make me who i am but they do determine a lot of things about my day to day life and how i act now. but i want you to know that you are more than your mental illness and you can get better. there’s no “fix” but there are ways to cope and just as importantly there are others. we are out there and you are not alone
professional or not. i am here and happy to answer dms or emails if you need someone
column4: i will be that someone. i have my someone and they saved my life and i mean that. don’t feel alone anymore
column5: you don’t have to be alone again.

column1: shoutout to @mikeymalonemotivatedmuscle for inspiring me to write this
column2: it’s not easy when it’s close to home

column1: 302442;instagram;2018-10-10 13:03:46;FALSE;"child sex abuse and sexual assault are extremely traumatic experiences that impacts one on a physical
column4: and spiritual level. the experience leaves survivors feeling unsafe
column6: how you've spoken about other survivors in their presence in the past can determine whether your child feels safe to disclose their abuse/assault to you. as parents
column7: words spoken directly and indirectly to our children matter. our words help shape their world; they shape how they see themselves
column8: and how they see others. and
column9: because we do not always communicate the way we should
column10: a lot of what we say is taken literally and they begin to formulate how we will behave or respond when certain situations arise. if you've made negative comments about other survivors or assigned blame to them
column11: your child will likely think that's how you'll respond to hearing about their abuse/assault as well. in order to expect your child to feel safe enough to come to you when someone has hurt them
column12: you must create an environment where they can be absolutely sure that they are completely safe with you and you won't shame them
column14: or call them a liar if they tell you they're being abused or have been abused in the past. beyond teaching boundaries/body autonomy and reassuring them that you will always believe them and make any harm being done to them stop
column15: you also have to be extremely mindful of what you say about survivors in your child's presence. they are listening and they believe you.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate";;en;#childsexabuseawareness

column1: 302448;instagram;2018-10-10 13:05:18;FALSE;"another #mymemorablemoments post. when i was in college
column2: i had an #epiphany while walking on a trail in the mountains of northern georgia. during a #womeninthewilderness #rockclimbing trip with #trip (travel & recreation program) at #universityofflorida
column3: i cried because i realized i finally knew what i wanted to do with the rest of my life. i wanted to #photograph people doing trips like that one. #transformational trips that encouraged us to face our #fears
column4: #daretolive and had a #support #network to help us move into #success through the tears of #breakthroughs. ....

column2: i photographed women who froze mid-climb because they told themselves they couldn’t go further. they were face-to-face with themselves. with the support of their climbing partner (literally the one holding the other end of the rope) and the rest of us on the trip
column3: they pushed through their limiting #selftalk & mental monkey chatter to reach the top of the climb
column4: tears streaming & cheering the victory of success. ....

column1: i cried while i was on that wall and later cried on the trail because i knew i would be traveling the world photographing people facing their fears & plowing through them. i would be there documenting the whole journey. the tears of resistance
column4: childhood scars. the tears of realization

column1: i am #honored that i am able to capture those #transformationalmoments in people’s lives. i am #creating the life of my dreams!!! #thankyou!!";;en;#MyMemorableMoments

column1: the year was 2007. i was 16-17 at that time. i had recently moved to a new place and a couple of blocks from my house lived this guy. i developed a 'major crush' on him as i found him good-looking. we used to chat and gossip on and off. he was around 22 and had recently cleared merchant navy or navy(i don't remember what precisely now). after some time i told him about my crush and 'he said he feels same'. we flirted a lot and one day decided to meet at his place when no one would be there. obviously the plan was for sex and i was pretty excited for it. i was a virgin then. the day i had got my 'periods'. when i reached his place i told him that we should not do the thing and perhaps only talk.
he kept on insisting and started removing my clothes. i told him not to many times but he kept continuing. somewhere in the middle of it
column2: i gave up and we did it.

column1: it was 'pretty rough' for the first time and i didn't really enjoy it. i know i really wanted to do it but when i told him that i was 'menstruating' i 'expected him to understand which he didn't'. either way
column2: he had some other girl friends as he was a 'polyamorous' and we soon stopped talking.

column1: i will always blame that guy for 'ruining my first time' and making it a bad mess. i had dreams of it to be 'special'. i never hoped for marriage or such promises from the person i wanted to give my virginity to
column2: my only expectation was a 'good first time'. i think 'everyone deserves that'. this is my story of 'violated consent'
column3: which i had bottled up inside me for so long. i want a 'flowing' of this 'trauma out of my mind' by voicing it out to the people who care for me. (based on the tale of miss. g)

ist da ich selber darüber bestimmen müsste dürfen und wenn leute mich zum reden zwingen wollen dann fragt den e gibt bestimmt methoden ohne körperverletzung kindesraub..außerdem habe ich darüber gerdet ... und es ist nicht nur bei gesicht wo andere bestimmen es zu enstellen sondern ich bekomme einen gang schaden und gesunde zähne werden esxchädigt ... hat ihrgendwer bnadjas körpergeschöfdigt und sie unter tägliche schmerzen gesetz für eine therapie die sie icht u niemand darf sich kaufen über andere menschen zu bestimmen sie tammen altdörfer dickmann zu verkaufen ! na inbpüchereien sieht ihr mein handy für internet ? ! die klimakonferenzen präsident heißt wo ich mir letztes jahr gewünscht hätte zu meinen gebustag mit mei sn sohn verbringen zu können ..aber ein mächtiger hat dafür bezahlt meine selbstbestimmungsrechte zu nehmen und mir diesis erlebniss mit meinen sohn zu stehlen und das tammen ein mädel geschickte hat als wir zur demo gefahren sind die wie meine kousine heisst patricia na und ! ? column1: i heard stories of life after death.
it seemed to make people eternal.
and i expected it to be a fairy tale
but none prepared me for the hell
i embraced death; one blow at a time;
a blow when i realised that your parents don't love you unconditionally
and that family comes with terms and conditions.
another blow when i realise that your best friend will beat you
the moment he becomes a possesive boyfriend.
a blow when they tore my clothes apart
even when there was no need for it.
and i finally died when he touched me
with a consent he never asked for
and now that i breathe every time
it's reminds me that i am dead.
and still breathing while dead; it makes me hate the eternity.
i wish i never wished for a life after death.

a blow when i realised that your parents do not love you unconditionally
and that family comes with terms and conditions.
another blow when i realise that your best friend will beat you

a blow when they tore my clothes apa
even when there was no need for it.
and i finally died when he touched me
with a consent he never asked for
and now that i breathe every time
it is reminds me that i am dead.
and still breathing while dead; it makes me hate the eternity.
i wish i never wished for a life after death.

column1: 302484;instagram;2018-10-10 12:46:20;FALSE;"hey everyone!  it’s been a while but school is going great!
i was super stoked to go today but when my bonus mom pulled up to drop me off to my driver it was a male we didn’t know and my aid wasn’t there either
column2: instead it was a guy we’ve never seen.

column1: i was super sad when we pulled away
column2: i was really looking forward to today.  my bonus mom said that riverview community school district told her they didn’t have anyone anymore to send with me.  they wanted me to ride in a car for an hour one way with men i didn’t know.  she also told me that the men were not trained to handle seizures

column1: i’m sad that my iep isn’t being followed and all the time and energy to make sure my schooling at cooke school is a success is going to waste while i sit and watch tv alone this week
why can’t the adults in charge of my future all be on the same page?  i’ve gone to cooke for 3 years now
column2: my needs haven’t changed.  would you want to sit in a car twice a day for an hour with men you didn’t know?  or have your daughter be in a car with men she didn’t know?

column1: i heard my bonus mom talking very loudly
column2: sounds like #riverviewtransportationdepartment told her to call trinity transportation to see why they sent a male aid.  she was very upset and kept asking why she has to follow up and do their job.

column4: without my friends and learning nothing
column5: as my peers are doing fun things and learning fun stuff.

column2: why would anyone be okay sending 2 grown men in a car for an hour with a nonverbal

column1: 302494;instagram;2018-10-10 12:49:01;FALSE;"i have a fear. you know what it is?
i have a fear. it's of getting raped.
i'm not a male or a female. you know who i am?
i'm not a gender first. i am a human which counts.
i'm being assaulted not as a gender.
i'm being assaulted as a human
that day i laid still. numb. thoughtless.
to him that was an advantage. he had an adventure that day.
can you hear my voice? i'm screaming so loud.
behind those tough hands covering my mouth.
can you see my tears. they're flowing as flood.
behind those dark rooms full of blood.
can you see me? i'm just few miles away.
behind those nasty thoughts that i couldn't say.
i want justice. can you hear that?
i don't want to hang him to death. it's nothing in front
of what he did to me.
can you put an end to it?
can you make it go diminished?
can you make me break my silence?
can you break the quote ""society kya sochegi?""

column2: still i'm afraid to move on the road alone with a fear of being raped.

column1: #girlpowerquotes #girlpower #girlslikeus #femalefirefighter";"i have a fear. you know what it is?
i have a fear. it is of getting raped.
i am not a male or a female. you know who i am?
i am not a gender first. i am a human which counts.
i am being assaulted not as a gender.
i am being assaulted as a human
that day i laid still. numb. thoughtless.
to him that was an advantage. he had an adventure that day.
can you hear my voice? i am screaming so loud.
behind those tough hands covering my mouth.
can you see my tears. they're flowing as flood.
behind those dark rooms full of blood.
can you see me? i am just few miles away.
behind those nasty thoughts that i couldn't say.
i want justice. can you hear that?
i do not want to hang him to death. it is nothing in front
of what he did to me.
can you put an end to it?
can you make it go diminished?
can you make me break my silence?
can you break the quote ""society kya sochegi?""

column1: 302498;instagram;2018-10-10 12:50:16;FALSE;"when i wake up in the middle of the night i have the hardest time bringing myself back to a resting state. i get energized and excited thinking about the day to come.
fullness has been corrupting my sleep because of how excited i am for all of the changes and growth that are coming.
i get excited about the changes i see happening in peoples lives.
i get restless recognizing how my friendships have developed and deepened through the conversations that are happening.
this season of fullness is one that i know i’ll miss someday. but for now i bask in it. and allow myself to be excited
ps stay tuned for the vulnerable post about how although there is so much excitement it doesn’t come without dips and lulls. .

column1: 302506;instagram;2018-10-10 07:52:58;FALSE;"sometimes you just want to sit in a nest and pretend the world doesn’t exist.
there’s so many reasons to be angry
column4: and lost with the world at the moment.

column1: it is unfathomable to me how dismissive people can still be about the treatment of women in our society.
we’ve sat and watched as dr christine blasey ford stated her testimony
column2: and so calmly recounted horrific details of sexual assault in her past
column3: only for brett kavanaugh to be found innocent and given a promotion. women protested. they raged. they cried. they shared their stories. and once again
we’ve had 6 women murdered in incidences of violence against women. this year already 62 women have died violent deaths. i read a great article recently that said ‘if this was terrorist acts
column4: we’d be calling it an issue of national security’. where is the outrage? ✨

column1: they say to rage. they say to speak out. everyone has a story
column2: even if they haven’t told you theirs. i know i do. i know others do. but there’s only so much rage we can give. only so much we can withstand. ✨

column1: i don’t know where we go from here or what we do now. but to everyone out there
column2: whether or not you have been able to verbalise or share your experiences
column3: please know i believe you. i stand with you. and i rage with you. there’s room in my nest for everybody 💖

column3: please know i believe you. i stand with you. and i rage with you. there’s room in my nest for everybody 💖

column1: 302507;instagram;2018-10-10 11:51:36;FALSE;"do you want to know a secret? ❤️
i have suffered from anxiety for most of my life. from the time i was a child
column2: not really wanting to sleep at any of my friends houses
column3: or staying home alone! definitely not! i had severe test anxiety all through school and even tested in to a remedial reading class in second grade. i had no “real reason” to be anxious. i came from an extremely loving and supporting family. we went to church regularly
column4: so i was close to god and new how to pray
column5: but still it got worse. finally
column6: as a freshman/sophmore in college it peaked! i remember laying in bed thinking i was crazy. what is wrong with me? why can’t i sleep? why can’t i drive my car? why can’t i be alone for a single second without having racing thoughts or a panic attack? i needed someone with me at all times. i remember being on a trip to philadelphia for the psha convention ( pennsylvania speech and hearing association) and literally having a panic attack on the street. by then it was holding me back from all of my dreams. everything i wanted or thought i could be. ❤️

column2: my mom recognized that something was going on. i wasn’t my happy go lucky self. i was shutting everyone out. my now husband @jrleach00 was my rock
column3: and ended up transferring colleges to be with me ( he won’t tell you that’s why). between the two of them they got me help. ❤️

column1: if you know me personally you most likely surprised by this entire story! i’ve tried to hide it my whole life. i’ve been embarrassed by it honestly
column2: but i know so many people out there are suffering! i want you to know you are not alone. ❤️

column1: i want all the young girls out there
column2: who tell themselves they are crazy
column3: and hide there anxiety from the world to know that there is another way. you don’t have to suffer through it! it’s a real disorder that can hinder your every hopes
column5: and cripple your future if you let it! don’t let it! get the help you need! 💋

column1: 302554;instagram;2018-10-10 12:09:23;FALSE;"البداية كانت في 13 يونيو 2009، حين اتصلت كاثرين مايورغا بشرطة لاس فيغاس عند الساعة 2:16 دقيقة، وأخبرتهم بأنها لا تريد الإعلان عن هوية الفاعل لكونه شخصية مشهورة، وقامت الشرطة بأخذها إلى المستشفى للقيام بفحوصات الاغتصاب.
في 12 يناير 2010، توصل محامي كريستيانو رونالدو ومحامي مايورغا إلى اتفاق خارج المحكمة يلتزم بموجبه الطرفان بعدم مناقشة الأمر وإقفال القضية وقام رونالدو بدفع 375000 دولار مقابل الاتفاق.

في 29 سبتمبر 2018، وذلك بعد 9 سنوات من القضية قررت مايورغا الخروج إلى العلن بعد حملة #metoo (أنا أيضًا) التي انتشرت بشكل واسع في الولايات المتحدة الأميركية، وجاء تصريحها تزامناً مع حصول مجلة دير شبيغل الألمانية على مستندات يظهر فيها نموذج أجوبة كريستيانو رونالدو، لم يتأخر اللاعب البرتغالي ليعلن محاميه أنه سيقوم بمقاضاة المجلة، إلا أن الضربة القاضية جاءت في 30 سبتمبر 2018 حين نشر الكاتب كريستوف وينترباخ 25 تغريدة تضمنت وثائق تُدين كريستيانو رونالدو.

في 1 أكتوبر 2018، قررت مايورغا مقاضاة رونالدو مجدداً وهو ما جعل العقد المبرم بينهما في السابق باطل حكماً، وبعد يوم واحد أعلنت شرطة لاس فيغاس إعادة فتح القضية التي لم تتابعها حينها لكون مايورغا لم تقدم معلومات حول ""مكان الحادثة ووصف المغتصب"".

بعد 11 يوماً على الحادثة خرجت مبررات بالجملة تحاول التقليل من أهمية ما حدث تحت عناوين مختلفة، منها أن كاثرين مايورغا كانت قبل الحادثة في سهرة مع رونالدو، أو التشكيك في توقيت إعادة فتح القضية كأن ذلك مرتبط بخروج رونالدو من ريال مدريد وانتقاله إلى يوفنتوس وأن ما يحدث هو استكمال لمؤامرة تضمنت خسارته لجائزة الأفضل في العالم لصالح مودريتش وتستمر الآن بتشويه صورته، أما أحد أهم المبررات الكارثية فهو أن كاثرين تُعيد فتح القضية لأجل الحصول على المال.

هي مبررات لا ترتقِ لحجم الفعل، خاصة في ظل ما تشير إليه الوثائق من إجابات رونالدو الواضحة في التحقيق التي نشرتها الصحيفة الألمانية ""لقد قالت لا تريد ذلك، لكنها جعلت نفسها متاحة، قالت لا أكثر من مرة، أنا لست مثل الجميع، ورداً على سؤال إذا كانت كاثرين قد اشتكت من معاملة وحشية، جاءت إجابة ""الدون"": لم تشتكِ من الوحشية، اشتكت من كوني ألزمتها على ذلك"".

إن كانت هذه الجمل التي نطقها رونالدو بنفسه غير كافية، فإن ورقة العقد الموقع من رونالدو في تاريخ 12 يناير 2010 (الصور أدناه) والذي دفع بموجبها 375000 دولار مقابل عدم الحديث في القضية والسكوت عنها هي الدليل الأهم.

";البداية كانت في 13 يونيو 2009، حين اتصلت كاثرين مايورغا بشرطة لاس فيغاس عند الساعة 2:16 دقيقة، وأخبرتهم بأنها لا تريد الإعلان عن هوية الفاعل لكونه شخصية مشهورة، وقامت الشرطة بأخذها إلى المستشفى للقيام بفحوصات الاغتصاب . في 12 يناير 2010، توصل محامي كريستيانو رونالدو ومحامي مايورغا إلى اتفاق خارج المحكمة يلتزم بموجبه الطرفان بعدم مناقشة الأمر وإقفال القضية وقام رونالدو بدفع 375000 دولار مقابل الاتفاق . في 29 سبتمبر 2018، وذلك بعد 9 سنوات من القضية قررت مايورغا الخروج إلى العلن بعد حملة ( أنا أيضًا ) التي انتشرت بشكل واسع في الولايات المتحدة الأميركية، وجاء تصريحها تزامناً مع حصول مجلة دير شبيغل الألمانية على مستندات يظهر فيها نموذج أجوبة كريستيانو رونالدو، لم يتأخر اللاعب البرتغالي ليعلن محاميه أنه سيقوم بمقاضاة المجلة، إلا أن الضربة القاضية جاءت في 30 سبتمبر 2018 حين نشر الكاتب كريستوف وينترباخ 25 تغريدة تضمنت وثائق تُدين كريستيانو رونالدو . في 1 أكتوبر 2018، قررت مايورغا مقاضاة رونالدو مجدداً وهو ما جعل العقد المبرم بينهما في السابق باطل حكماً، وبعد يوم واحد أعلنت شرطة لاس فيغاس إعادة فتح القضية التي لم تتابعها حينها لكون مايورغا لم تقدم معلومات حول `` مكان الحادثة ووصف المغتصب '' . بعد 11 يوماً على الحادثة خرجت مبررات بالجملة تحاول التقليل من أهمية ما حدث تحت عناوين مختلفة، منها أن كاثرين مايورغا كانت قبل الحادثة في سهرة مع رونالدو، أو التشكيك في توقيت إعادة فتح القضية كأن ذلك مرتبط بخروج رونالدو من ريال مدريد وانتقاله إلى يوفنتوس وأن ما يحدث هو استكمال لمؤامرة تضمنت خسارته لجائزة الأفضل في العالم لصالح مودريتش وتستمر الآن بتشويه صورته، أما أحد أهم المبررات الكارثية فهو أن كاثرين تُعيد فتح القضية لأجل الحصول على المال . هي مبررات لا ترتقِ لحجم الفعل، خاصة في ظل ما تشير إليه الوثائق من إجابات رونالدو الواضحة في التحقيق التي نشرتها الصحيفة الألمانية `` لقد قالت لا تريد ذلك، لكنها جعلت نفسها متاحة، قالت لا أكثر من مرة، أنا لست مثل الجميع، ورداً على سؤال إذا كانت كاثرين قد اشتكت من معاملة وحشية، جاءت إجابة `` الدون '' : لم تشتكِ من الوحشية، اشتكت من كوني ألزمتها على ذلك '' . إن كانت هذه الجمل التي نطقها رونالدو بنفسه غير كافية، فإن ورقة العقد الموقع من رونالدو في تاريخ 12 يناير 2010 ( الصور أدناه ) والذي دفع بموجبها 375000 دولار مقابل عدم الحديث في القضية والسكوت عنها هي الدليل الأهم . وفنتوس ;[('البداية'

column1: 302592;instagram;2018-10-10 11:44:51;FALSE;"the biggest lesson i learned in life through my circumstances was that there are some things i was not meant to carry.

the burden i carried because of the abuse i experienced as a child was never mine to carry. agreeing to ""play a game"" as a kid led to an unfortunate circumstance and made me question every decision i made based on what someone else would do.
but my ""yes"" didn't cause the effects i experienced. someone else's sinful choice was not mine to be weighed down by.
if a drunk driver hits me; it's not my fault
column2: but it is on me to go to the hospital and take whatever rehabilitation might be needed.

column1: but i can't take responsibility for their decision. i can't hold on to that shame. i can't replay every decision i ""could have made"" to prevent the situation.
you weren't meant to carry that
column2: fam. i feel like someone needed to hear that!

column1: know what is yours and what isn't and take it all to the lord.

302603;instagram;2018-10-10 11:50:06;FALSE;a marketing and life lesson from one of my very favorite women — 👯‍♀️
we are taught that we need to be *perfect* in order to be happy.
our pictures need to be beautiful.
our bodies need to be a certain way.
our careers need to be corporate.
our relationship needs to be happy.
which is actually hilarious because the more i have relationships and also coach lots of women to heal their relationship pain....
the more i realize how messy relationships are. and how messy life can be.
and it’s just like great marketing.
my favorite pictures of marilyn monroe are her candid shots.
the lighting might be off in some of them

so naturally perfect as she is.
so what i’m saying is embrace the mess that is you and fall in love with where you are right now.
if you’re not happy with something
column2: decide right now you’re going to change it + come talk to me because i can help you do this 😉

column1: today like any other day we try to raise awareness of mental illnesses. we have to realise everyone has a brain therefore everyone has mental health.

1 in 4 will develop a mental illness

for example cancelling plans last minute because i physically cannot leave the house due to anxiety even though i really want to see friends.
or having to leave a room because i can feel a flashback or panic attack coming on and i don’t want to feel embarrassed or panic others.
mental illnesses come in all forms. if someone is brave enough to open up to you
column2: listen and don’t judge them. if you don’t know how to help then that’s fine there a resources and support available for you and them.

column1: 302644;instagram;2018-10-10 11:25:51;FALSE;"i truly debated with myself on whether i should post this or not
column2: but it’s time i use my voice. i want to show my girls that they can be brave and speak up if and when needed.

column1: i was excited to see @goodr release some new shades for a cause. they teamed up with @breakingsilence_sos to encourage people to use their words and speak up so we can take preventative action against interpersonal violence.
why is this important to me? as a young child
column2: i was a victim of sexual assault. there may be two or three people in the course of my lifetime that i have actually told this story. my parents and many other family members are potentially reading/seeing/hearing about this for the first time. i am a male and am 41 now and have waited over 30 years to finally break my silence.

column1: the man who molested me was family. he was my aunt’s husband. my parents had dropped me off at their house. after a while
column2: he decided i was his play thing and could do whatever he wanted with me. this happened two or three more times. i don’t recall why i stopped going over there
column3: but it was by the grace of god that it ended.

column1: why didn’t i speak up then? it’s simple. i was scared. again
column2: he was family. i didn’t think anyone would believe a family member was capable of such evil.

column1: why am i speaking up now? i have no reason other than being inspired by a pair of sunglasses. yes
column2: even the little things can be motivating. do i wish i would have said something as a kid? hell yeah. even though i have been fortunate to not have had these incidents haunt me
column3: it may not be the same for anyone else this man may have assaulted after me.

column1: none of you are alone in this
column2: and this includes other men as well. be brave. speak up. use your words. if not for yourself
column3: do it for the potential victims down the line to whom you can prevent this violence from happening.

why is this important to me? as a young child
column2: i was a victim of sexual assault. there may be two or three people in the course of my lifetime that i have actually told this story. my parents and many other family members are potentially reading/seeing/hearing about this for the first time. i am a male and am 41 now and have waited over 30 years to finally break my silence.

column1: the man who molested me was family. he was my aunt’s husband. my parents had dropped me off at their house. after a while
column2: he decided i was his play thing and could do whatever he wanted with me. this happened two or three more times. i don’t recall why i stopped going over there
column3: but it was by the grace of god that it ended.

column1: why didn’t i speak up then? it’s simple. i was scared. again
column2: he was family. i didn’t think anyone would believe a family member was capable of such evil.

column1: why am i speaking up now? i have no reason other than being inspired by a pair of sunglasses. yes
column2: even the little things can be motivating. do i wish i would have said something as a kid? hell yeah. even though i have been fortunate to not have had these incidents haunt me
column3: it may not be the same for anyone else this man may have assaulted after me.

column1: 302709;instagram;2018-10-10 10:30:45;FALSE;"關注婦女性暴力協會對於《2018施政報告》未能回應下述四點議題感到不能接受，就此作出簡短回應：
1. 法律改革方面，在施政報告並無回應任何法改會性罪行改革小組已提出的諮詢文件，包括《強姦及其他未經同意下的進行的性行為》、《涉及兒童及無行為能力人士的性罪行》、《雜項性罪行》，法改會展開了性罪行法例改革工作已經長達6年，可惜一直未有落實時間表，政府也未作出過任何回應。
2. 在處理性暴力方面，施政報告只提及協助少數族裔應對家暴及性暴力，但是未有對整體性暴力預防教育及打擊性罪行的計劃及資源分配。自從 #metoo 運動在香港引起廣泛關注和討論，有性暴力受害者在網上講出自己的經歷。但當受害人講出經歷時，往往招徠很多隱藏性暴力迷思的責罵，政府卻似乎無視這個現象，沒有做出任何行動反省如何改善現存制度，以消除性暴力。
3. 性傾向歧視立法方面，施政報告未有就《性傾向歧視條例》定下立法的工作時間表。政府再次以進行諮詢及研討需時作為藉口，漠視不同民間及學術機構的研究成果及建議，例如2016年由平機會委託中大性別研究中心公佈的立法研討報告。可惜，政府無視這一切的研討成果及社會需求，對立法採取迴避態度。我們要求政府盡快提出相關的立法時間表。
4. 性教育方面，本會認為合適的性教育應發展為全面性教育，在生理層面以外更應包含性知識、性別平等教育，並提供非批判和安全環境讓年青人思考和討論。以及加強相關專業人士如社工及老師的性教育培訓，以營造一個對不同性別、性傾向和性別認同人士均友善的學習環境。

column28: 'NN')];關注婦女性暴力協會對於《2018施政報告》未能回應下述四點議題感到不能接受，就此作出簡短回應： 1 . 法律改革方面，在施政報告並無回應任何法改會性罪行改革小組已提出的諮詢文件，包括《強姦及其他未經同意下的進行的性行為》、《涉及兒童及無行為能力人士的性罪行》、《雜項性罪行》，法改會展開了性罪行法例改革工作已經長達6年，可惜一直未有落實時間表，政府也未作出過任何回應。 2 . 在處理性暴力方面，施政報告只提及協助少數族裔應對家暴及性暴力，但是未有對整體性暴力預防教育及打擊性罪行的計劃及資源分配。自從 運動在香港引起廣泛關注和討論，有性暴力受害者在網上講出自己的經歷。但當受害人講出經歷時，往往招徠很多隱藏性暴力迷思的責罵，政府卻似乎無視這個現象，沒有做出任何行動反省如何改善現存制度，以消除性暴力。 3 . 性傾向歧視立法方面，施政報告未有就《性傾向歧視條例》定下立法的工作時間表。政府再次以進行諮詢及研討需時作為藉口，漠視不同民間及學術機構的研究成果及建議，例如2016年由平機會委託中大性別研究中心公佈的立法研討報告。可惜，政府無視這一切的研討成果及社會需求，對立法採取迴避態度。我們要求政府盡快提出相關的立法時間表。 4 . 性教育方面，本會認為合適的性教育應發展為全面性教育，在生理層面以外更應包含性知識、性別平等教育，並提供非批判和安全環境讓年青人思考和討論。以及加強相關專業人士如社工及老師的性教育培訓，以營造一個對不同性別、性傾向和性別認同人士均友善的學習環境。;關注婦女性暴力協會對於《2018施政報告》未能回應下述四點議題感到不能接受，就此作出簡短回應： 1 . 法律改革方面，在施政報告並無回應任何法改會性罪行改革小組已提出的諮詢文件，包括《強姦及其他未經同意下的進行的性行為》、《涉及兒童及無行為能力人士的性罪行》、《雜項性罪行》，法改會展開了性罪行法例改革工作已經長達6年，可惜一直未有落實時間表，政府也未作出過任何回應。 2 . 在處理性暴力方面，施政報告只提及協助少數族裔應對家暴及性暴力，但是未有對整體性暴力預防教育及打擊性罪行的計劃及資源分配。自從 運動在香港引起廣泛關注和討論，有性暴力受害者在網上講出自己的經歷。但當受害人講出經歷時，往往招徠很多隱藏性暴力迷思的責罵，政府卻似乎無視這個現象，沒有做出任何行動反省如何改善現存制度，以消除性暴力。 3 . 性傾向歧視立法方面，施政報告未有就《性傾向歧視條例》定下立法的工作時間表。政府再次以進行諮詢及研討需時作為藉口，漠視不同民間及學術機構的研究成果及建議，例如2016年由平機會委託中大性別研究中心公佈的立法研討報告。可惜，政府無視這一切的研討成果及社會需求，對立法採取迴避態度。我們要求政府盡快提出相關的立法時間表。 4 . 性教育方面，本會認為合適的性教育應發展為全面性教育，在生理層面以外更應包含性知識、性別平等教育，並提供非批判和安全環境讓年青人思考和討論。以及加強相關專業人士如社工及老師的性教育培訓，以營造一個對不同性別、性傾向和性別認同人士均友善的學習環境。

column1: 302721;instagram;2018-10-05 15:22:56;FALSE;"*we do what we like. don't read between the lines.* .
red is not an invitation. red is not a pigment of judgement. red is not regret. red is a preference. strong. bold. vibrant.
every time i wore red lipstick
column2: my uncle would tell me a story about how the men in my area had once eve teased a woman when she’d walked out of her house with dark lipstick.
my teachers told me to wear pants underneath my skirt and a full sleeved sweater in the hot sun because my skin show was distracting studious young boys.
my ex thought i shouldn’t wear a dress because men look at my legs and it was my fault.

column1: i have been molested. i have been abused. but all this happened even when i was 8.

column2: baby body in a fully covering suit?

column1: why didn’t you blame men who eve teased her and why didn’t you protect her?
are you teaching the boys that it is okay to be provoked around less clothing? that it is normal to get distracted and it all depends on the woman’s clothes?
do you think it’s normal for men to look at women because that’s what you did all life? do you not understand that ogling is an offence and wearing a dress isn’t.
it’s high time. if you don’t know it yet
the only way to touch me is to take my consent.
stop victim blaming. stop defending molesters in the name of victim blaming.
lipstick is my way of feeling empowered. be a part of it.
be a part of the red lipstick squad.
this is my story. what’s yours?
tell me your story and hashtag :thegirlwiththeredlipstick and tag me! the world will know you’re not alone in this :) also if you haven’t pre-ordered your copy yet

column1: why didn’t you blame men who eve teased her and why didn’t you protect her?
are you teaching the boys that it is okay to be provoked around less clothing? that it is normal to get distracted and it all depends on the woman’s clothes?
do you think it’s normal for men to look at women because that’s what you did all life? do you not understand that ogling is an offence and wearing a dress isn’t.
it’s high time. if you don’t know it yet
the only way to touch me is to take my consent.
stop victim blaming. stop defending molesters in the name of victim blaming.
lipstick is my way of feeling empowered. be a part of it.
be a part of the red lipstick squad.
this is my story. what’s yours?

my ex thought i shouldn’t wear a dress because men look at my legs and it was my fault.

column1: 302730;instagram;2018-10-10 09:51:27;FALSE;"on the outside i look like any other ordinary
column3: person. on the inside my soul has been shattered into a thousand pieces
column4: shards remain of what once was whole. every day i torture myself with thoughts that serve no purpose. every day i fight against this intrusion
column5: to not let them take control. some days i win
column6: some days i lose but i keep going. it's exhausting. little by little i'm sticking the pieces back together and one day i will be whole. there will be cracks
column7: some bits will fall away and the shape will be different but that's ok. i'm good with that.

column1: i initially chose the name relovingrachel because i had designs on writing a blog on mental health. on finding ways to love myself and discovering who i really am. i wear many masks and i wanted to peel them all away. over the years i have invested a lot of time and energy in self-loathing. i've put a lot of effort in to placing a label on me. to finding a disorder that explains why i behave the way i do. because i needed a reason. how could i be this tortured and not have a label to fit snugly in to??? mental health issues are complex. it took me until this year to come to terms with one size does not fit all. i found the cause of my pain. i knew it all along but couldn't face it being my epicentre. but now i know what to do and i accept that there will be many days ahead that i can't face life. then the sun will rise again.
i decided against the blog. it feels like a lot of effort for me right now. painting furniture is my therapy. taking something battered and unwanted
column2: filling in some of the holes
column3: leaving others untouched where it's character shines through and giving it a new lease of life. it fills me with joy. so that is what i'll do ❤

column1: much love to @nina_in_the_nest for starting this conversation. i feel very passionate about sharing experiences. it's what makes us stronger xx

column2: which i’ve taken in my back patio this morning - is a copy of the book that shifted things for me when i was experiencing the worst of my own mental health problems. i also recommend watching @oprah ’s interview of @eckharttolle - the author.  next to that is a beautiful card from the @bycacademy that says “be yourself always” - i was so pleased to see that “accept who you are” was one of the recommendations made in the guide i’ve linked in my bio to improve mental health. i couldn’t agree more - the reason the power of now helped me was because for the first time i truly got it that i could do nothing to change my past and it was my worry (anxiety) about the future and my guilt/shame/resentment (depression) about the  past - that was causing my current suffering. if i let go of my stories
column3: if i simply focussed on living in this present moment & accepted things as they are
column4: including myself - then i could experience peace

column2: i thought i would stopped by the shop to get some wrap for lunch. i ordered the chicken wrap.

column1: the chicken wrap ($48) took some time to prep
column2: while i was really excited for the grilled chicken but was quite let down by the meat quality. it was dry and rather tasteless. i didn't notice it had raw onion on the menu description so i am left with a bad breath throughout my work day.

column1: what also left a bad taste in my mouth is the ""unprofessional"" event i witnessed during my brief lunch. a tall man
column2: assuming to be the manager of the store
column3: came out of the back room and casually
column4: but loudly smacked one of the kitchen girls' butt. i was horrified to see and hear the loud smacking. everyone marched on with their day as if nothing happened. while i cannot assume the relationship between the two said employees
column5: i really don't think this kind of behaviour is deemed appropriate in the #metoo era. i am writing this review because 1) i hope the management will take notice 2) if said tall man is indeed ""the management""
column6: pls stop your casual ""horsing around"" behavior. you are at a sandwich shop
column7: not a night club. please keep your bedroom behavior in your bedroom. 90% of the walk-in patrons are girls. i don't know in what world this is ok.

column1: 302910;instagram;2018-10-10 07:08:25;FALSE;i was married to a narcisist and an abuser. i was isolated from my friends and family. i was told i was fat
column3: that i was worthless. i was told i was a terrible mother. i was the only one working yet not allowed to access any money. many times during my marriage i was working 2-3 jobs. i would lose jobs because of him. i had trouble keeping a job. i was then ridiculed because i couldn't hold down a job that he cost me. he would show up at my job
column4: sometimes multiple times a day. at the end of my marriage i was raped. multiple times. not allowed to leave the house. restricted on when i was allowed to use the restroom or take a shower. i was not allowed to eat. i was not allowed to have a cell phone because it was disconnected. when i finally got out of the house and tried getting a restraining order and tried to get help the judge denied it because i was able to leave the house to file for the restraining order. when i filed for divorce the judge in my case didn't believe me because the first judge denied the restraining order. he wouldn't talk to my children who witnessed the abuse. the judge over my divorce proceedings didn't believe in marital rape. the judge advised i seek psychiatric help because he thought i had a mental disorder. my abuser sits at home and collects a disability check for schitzoaffective disorder while i work two full-time jobs to make ends meet. my abuser got custody of our children because the judge said i needed psychiatric help
column5: that i was too sick to have custody because i was going through chemo treatments. but i was still ordered to pay child support and i work two jobs to try and pay bills. my abuser collects $3500/month between disibilty and child support. i received no justice. the judges did not believe me. my children are suffering because of the judges decision and the judge will not review his ruling. i fight every day and advocate for domestic violence victims because i have been there. my children will never go without no matter how hard i have to work. no matter how many hours i must put in. because even though they go without at their fathers house
column6: they will no go without at mine. #takeastand #metoo;;en;#takeastand

column1: 302921;instagram;2018-10-10 07:12:24;FALSE;"why do we love stories so much?
the number one reason we love stories is that we feel empathy for the characters.
empathy is distinct from sympathy. it doesn't mean 'liking' the characters necessarily. it means seeing parts of ourselves in them
some of the best storytellers (fictional & biographical) are skilled in empathy as it requires the ability to: take on different perspectives
column3: and understand the feelings of another. often some of the best stories are those that have a character that is not likeable yet we feel the tension when we connect with them around a shared human concern. conversely
column4: we may feel more connection to a likeable character when we see that we share similar flaws or shortcomings.

column2: “empathy is the skill or ability to tap into our own experiences in order to connect with an experience someone is relating to us. compassion is the willingness to be open to the process.” and if our compassion is the willingness to be open to empathy
column3: perhaps the means to grow more compassion in our world is story? #empathy #compassion #powerofvulnerability #powerofstory #human #vulnerability #metoo #memoir #perspective #story";;en;#empathy

column1: ...& then begins the arduous journey to the summit. climbing rocks
column3: often stumbling and slipping. pushing yourself through downpours. being treated by moments of beauty and clarity.

column1: you reach the summit after one last big push & hopefully you’re treated to the most glorious view & a huge feeling of achievement & pride.
the feeling is addictive and you want it to continue & so you carry on along your path of self awareness and grow your confidence & independence.
this is what mountain hiking is for me. it’s opening my mind. letting out the sorrows of times gone past & making space for now & the future.
we all need to find our own ways of growing as humans but we also need to support each other. life is tough. but we are tough too

column1: क्यों सुनके अनसुनी की थी तुमने वो पुकार
जो चिल्ला चिल्ला कर मांग रही थी तुमसे न्याय
उस दर्द भरी पुकार को तुमने कर दिया बर्बाद
जो तुमसे पूँछ रही थी कुछ सवाल
उसको खबर न थी कि यहाँ दानवों की कितनी आबादी है

column2: पर दानव को पूरी आजादी है

column1: आखिर उस पर क्यों किया इतना बड़ा अत्याचार
अब तो थोड़ी शर्म कर लो सीख लो थोडा शिष्टाचार
उठा पाती मैं तलवार यदि तो
वीरांगना बन जाती मैं और एसी दुर्गति करती उनकी
कि वो कभी भूल न पाते ।
we are thankful to @soulful_speech for sharing such amazing content with us.
